..TEXT:
Pisistratus, the tyrant of Athens, who used his
power so nobly as to make the people forget the usurpation by
which he had attained it.  Among his good deeds was the
collection and preservation of the Homeric poems, which but for
him might have perished.  He was also the first to found a public
library in Athens.  This anecdote is told by Valerius Maximus,
^Fact. ac Dict.^, VI. 1.
